{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"daa72dd4-c070-4e74-9911-0e6f2ac1f001","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for **Apple's built-in crash reports**:\n\n1. **Crash logs** are saved automatically by macOS at:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS).\n\n2. **Console.app** → Sidebar → **Crash Reports** lets you browse them with a GUI.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited   # enable before running your app\n   ```\n   Cores land in `/cores/core.<pid>`. You can open them with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./YourApp -c /cores/core.12345\n   ```\n\nSince NativeAOT produces a native binary, standard macOS/LLDB crash analysis tools work directly — no .NET-specific tooling like `createdump` is needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fa85cb74-37fb-4da4-9d7f-d56c66fb197e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":299,"requestId":"9423:634EC:18042DD:1B58BC7:69E81F93"},"id":"84c0154a-f5f1-4044-8b33-77168f8f6b0d","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:08:43.338Z","parentId":"da438d85-593d-4c66-8ca5-e8ce5c626067"}
